ht">mesh build</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"text-align: left;" class=3D"confluenceTd"><h2 id=3D"Stepstobui=
lda.NetKafkaProducer-9"><strong>9</strong></h2></td>
<td style=3D"text-align: left;" class=3D"confluenceTd">
<div class=3D"content-wrapper">
<h2 id=3D"Stepstobuilda.NetKafkaProducer-DeploytheProducer"><strong>Deploy =
the Producer&nbsp;</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>Go to the component repository in cmd prompt.</li>
<li>Execute 'mesh deploy' command and provide the intended environment, bui=
ld number.</li>
</ul><br>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">mesh deploy</b><span class=3D"collapse-source expan=
d-control" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expand-control-icon icon"=
>&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expand source</span></spa=
n><span class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: bash; gutter: true; theme: Midnight; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"Midnig=
ht">mesh deploy -e &lt;environment to deploy&gt; -b &lt;build number of the=
 artifact to deploy&gt;</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"text-align: left;" class=3D"confluenceTd"><h2 id=3D"Stepstobui=
lda.NetKafkaProducer-10"><strong>10</strong></h2></td>
<td style=3D"text-align: left;" class=3D"confluenceTd"><h2 id=3D"Stepstobui=
lda.NetKafkaProducer-.NetKafkaProducerandSwimlaneSupport"><strong>.Net Kafk=
a Producer and Swimlane </strong><strong>Support</strong></h2><p>Westpac Me=
sh treats .Net Kafka producer as a capability that enriches an API to produ=
ce messages to a Kafka topic. Just like any other Westpac Mesh API, .Net Ka=
fka producer API also supports virtual swimlanes. The process to enroll, de=
ploy, and undeploy a swimlane is the same as that of a normal API. Refer to=
 Mesh Developer tools<span>&nbsp;</span><a href=3D"https://confluence.srv.w=
estpac.com.au/display/MESH/Mesh+Developer+Tools" rel=3D"nofollow">documenta=
tion</a>&nbsp;for swimlane operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style=3D"text-align: left;" class=3D"confluenceTd"><h2 id=3D"Stepstobui=
lda.NetKafkaProducer-11"><strong>11</strong></h2></td>
<td style=3D"text-align: left;" class=3D"confluenceTd">
<div class=3D"content-wrapper">
<h2 id=3D"Stepstobuilda.NetKafkaProducer-TestingProducerCodeLocally"><stron=
g>Testing Producer Code Locally</strong></h2>
<p>A producer can be run from on your local workstation, just like any othe=
r API.</p>
<p>All the ACLs required to post events to a topic are configured by the de=
ploy pipeline. Hence to run locally, as a prerequisite, your producer code =
should be deployed to dev1<strong><span>&nbsp;</span>at least</strong><span=
>&nbsp;</span>once.</p>
<ul>
<li>Copy the entries from the logs of 'Kafka - Configure Access' step in th=
e dev deploy pipeline.</li>
<li>Create a file named 'wdp-kafka-secrets.json' in secrets/local folder an=
d copy the 'username' and 'password' property from the logs of 'Kafka - Con=
figure Access' step in the dev deploy pipeline.</li>
<li>Contact BAU for password to connect to dev environment and place it in =
the 'password' property of&nbsp; 'wdp-kafka-secrets.json'.</li>
<li>Run the producer normally like any other .Net API</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Note: </strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Currently, Producer can be tested from local machine, provided that top=
ic is available on enterprise confluent (non confluent cloud).</li>
</ul>
<div id=3D"expander-1039303019" class=3D"expand-container">
